✅ THE COMMAND YOU MUST RUN
Open Command Prompt as Administrator, then run:

Code
install.bat oledb C:\Oracle\ODAC19 myhome true
This does 3 things:

Installs OraOLEDB (the Oracle OLE DB provider SSIS needs)

Installs all dependent components

Registers the provider in Windows registry

After this, SSIS will finally recognize:

Code
Oracle Provider for OLE DB
OraOLEDB.Oracle
📌 Step‑by‑Step Instructions (Follow EXACTLY)
1️⃣ Create the Oracle home folder
Before running the installer, create the folder:

Code
C:\Oracle\ODAC19
If it already exists, skip this step.

2️⃣ Open Command Prompt as Administrator
Start → type cmd → right‑click → Run as administrator

3️⃣ Navigate to your ODAC folder
From your log:

Code
C:\Users\skanao\OneDrive - Toronto Transit Commission\Downloads\ODAC19.29Xcopy_x64
So run:

Code
cd "C:\Users\skanao\OneDrive - Toronto Transit Commission\Downloads\ODAC19.29Xcopy_x64"
(Quotes required because of spaces.)

4️⃣ Run the install command
Now run:

Code
install.bat oledb C:\Oracle\ODAC19 myhome true
Breakdown:

oledb → installs OraOLEDB provider

C:\Oracle\ODAC19 → Oracle home

myhome → Oracle home name

true → install dependencies

5️⃣ RESTART WINDOWS
This step is mandatory.

Oracle OLE DB will not register until after reboot.

🔍 How to verify installation after reboot
✔ Check 1 — DLL exists
Look for:

Code
C:\Oracle\ODAC19\oledb\OraOLEDB19.dll
✔ Check 2 — Registry exists
Open regedit → navigate to:

Code
